// Śaṅkara (Advaita) commentary position summaries — chapters 13–18.
// Paraphrase-quality summaries of Ādi Śaṅkara's bhāṣya readings, NOT
// direct quotations. Audit and tighten over time.
export const SHANKARA_PART_3 = {
  // ── Chapter 13 — Kṣetra-Kṣetrajña Vibhāga Yoga ──────────────────────
  '13.1': "Śaṅkara opens the chapter by fixing its scope: the body is the kṣetra (field), and what knows it is the kṣetrajña (knower-of-the-field). This dyad is the entire Advaitic frame — discriminate the seen from the seer, and liberation follows.",
  '13.2': "He identifies the kṣetrajña in every body with the supreme Self (paramātman); the apparent multiplicity of knowers is upādhi-induced, not real. Right knowledge for him is precisely this discrimination of kṣetra from kṣetrajña, and that alone he calls jñāna.",
  '13.3': "Śaṅkara reads this verse as the chapter's table of contents: what the field is, of what nature, what its modifications are, whence it arises — and likewise for the knower. He stresses that the listing is provisional pedagogy preparing the listener for the non-dual conclusion.",
  '13.4': "He notes that the field-and-knower teaching is not Kṛṣṇa's innovation but is sung by ṛṣis, in varied Vedic metres, and especially in the reasoned, well-determined Brahma-sūtra padas. Śruti, smṛti, and nyāya converge on one truth.",
  '13.5': "The kṣetra is enumerated as the great elements, ahaṁkāra, buddhi, the unmanifest prakṛti, the eleven indriyas, and the five sense-objects. For Śaṅkara every item here is anātman — none of it is the Self, all of it is the seen.",
  '13.6': "Desire, aversion, pleasure, pain, the aggregate body, cognition, and steadfastness are likewise placed in the kṣetra. Even saṁghāta (the body-mind composite) and dhṛti are objects of the knower, not the knower itself.",
  '13.7': "Humility, unpretentiousness, non-injury, forbearance, uprightness, service of the teacher, purity, steadiness, self-control — Śaṅkara calls these the means to jñāna and so themselves jñāna by metonymy: that whose presence yields knowledge is called knowledge.",
  '13.8': "Dispassion toward sense-objects, absence of egoism, and constant awareness of the suffering inherent in birth, death, old age, and disease — Śaṅkara reads this as vairāgya forced upon the discerning mind by clear-sighted analysis of saṁsāra.",
  '13.9': "Non-attachment to son, wife, and home, and equanimity in the desirable and undesirable — for Śaṅkara, the householder's snares are not denounced as evil, only as binding so long as one identifies with them.",
  '13.10': "Unwavering devotion to Īśvara via single-pointed yoga, resort to solitary places, and aversion to crowded society are listed as further means. Śaṅkara takes ananyayoga here as the niṣṭhā that fixes the mind on the one Self.",
  '13.11': "Constancy in adhyātma-jñāna and insight into the goal of tattva-jñāna — Śaṅkara names this final item the very fruit of the preceding twenty: the rest are sādhana, this one alone is siddhi.",
  '13.12': "Now the jñeya — the object of knowledge — is announced: the beginningless supreme brahman, called neither sat nor asat. Śaṅkara reads na sat na asat as a denial of all empirical predicates, since brahman is beyond the very categories of being and non-being as those terms are normally understood.",
  '13.13': "With hands, feet, eyes, heads, and faces everywhere, brahman pervades all. Śaṅkara takes the apparent attribution of limbs as figurative — the indwelling Self is the witness present in every locus, not literally many-limbed.",
  '13.14': "Brahman shines forth as the qualities of all the senses, yet is itself devoid of senses; unattached, yet supports all; without guṇas, yet experiences guṇas. Śaṅkara reads each line as an apparent paradox dissolved by upādhi-vāda — the qualifications belong to the limiting adjuncts, not to the Self.",
  '13.15': "Outside and inside all beings, moving and unmoving, near and far — for Śaṅkara, the apparent paradoxes hold only because brahman is non-spatial and non-temporal; once the upādhi-frame is dropped, no contradiction remains.",
  '13.16': "Undivided, yet appearing divided in beings; supporter, devourer, and producer — Śaṅkara takes 'appearing divided' as the entire saṁsāra-image, an illusion produced by māyā, while the truth remains undivided.",
  '13.17': "Light of lights, beyond darkness, knowledge itself, the object of knowledge, attainable through knowledge, seated in the heart of all — for Śaṅkara, jyotiṣām api tat jyotiḥ names brahman as the final illuminator behind even sun, moon, and fire.",
  '13.18': "The kṣetra, jñāna, and jñeya have been told in brief; the bhakta who knows this becomes fit for Kṛṣṇa's bhāva. Śaṅkara reads madbhāvāya not as a heaven but as identity with the inmost Self — i.e., mokṣa.",
  '13.19': "Both prakṛti and puruṣa are beginningless, and the modifications and guṇas arise from prakṛti. Śaṅkara is careful: 'beginningless' here means without temporal origin, not metaphysically equal — prakṛti is the seen, puruṣa the seer.",
  '13.20': "Prakṛti is said to be the cause in the production of body and indriyas; puruṣa is the cause in the experiencing of pleasure and pain. For Śaṅkara, even the puruṣa's apparent enjoyership is upādhi-induced — the Self is by nature unattached.",
  '13.21': "The puruṣa, seated in prakṛti, experiences her guṇas; attachment to the guṇas is the cause of birth in good or evil wombs. Śaṅkara reads this whole transmigratory drama as a spectacle of the unreal upādhis, not a real fate of the Self.",
  '13.22': "The supreme puruṣa in this body is called witness, consenter, supporter, experiencer, the great lord, and paramātman. Śaṅkara takes upadraṣṭā literally — a near, uninvolved witness who simply watches the kṣetra's drama unfold.",
  '13.23': "Whoever knows puruṣa and prakṛti with her guṇas thus, however he may be living, is not born again. Śaṅkara takes this as a categorical jīvanmukti claim: jñāna burns the seed of rebirth regardless of one's external station.",
  '13.24': "Some perceive the Self in the self by the self through meditation, others by sāṅkhya-yoga, others by karma-yoga. Śaṅkara accepts the plurality of paths but ranks dhyāna and sāṅkhya as direct means and karma-yoga as a remoter aid.",
  '13.25': "Others, unaware of these methods, worship having heard from elders, and even they cross saṁsāra by śravaṇa-niṣṭhā. Śaṅkara reads this as a concession that even śraddhā in the teaching, properly clung to, eventually delivers.",
  '13.26': "Whatever being is born, moving or unmoving, know that it has come to be from the union of kṣetra and kṣetrajña. Śaṅkara: every empirical individual is a saṁyoga-figure, an apparent product of the seen and the seer's reflection, and is therefore unreal as such.",
  '13.27': "He who sees the supreme Lord seated equally in all beings, undying among the dying, truly sees. For Śaṅkara, samaṁ paśyan is the central viṣama-darśana-rejection: the ground is one, only the upādhis differ.",
  '13.28': "Seeing the Lord equally everywhere, he does not injure the Self by the self, and so reaches the supreme goal. Śaṅkara reads ātmānaṁ ātmanā na hinasti as the cessation of self-deception that anātman is ātman — that is the only real injury.",
  '13.29': "All actions are performed by prakṛti alone; the Self is not the doer. Śaṅkara takes this as the Gītā's clearest non-doership statement: kartṛtva belongs to upādhis, never to the witness.",
  '13.30': "When one sees the manifold existence of beings as resting in the One, and as spreading out from It, one attains brahman. For Śaṅkara, ekastham is the heart of the matter — non-dual seeing is brahma-prāpti, not a future reward but its present form.",
  '13.31': "Beginningless and guṇa-less, the supreme Self, even though seated in the body, neither acts nor is tainted. Śaṅkara stresses śarīra-stho 'pi — the appearance of embodiment does not affect the unembodied truth.",
  '13.32': "As space, though everywhere, is not tainted because of its subtlety, so the Self in every body is not tainted. Śaṅkara is fond of this ākāśa-dṛṣṭānta: subtlety here means non-association, not size.",
  '13.33': "As the one sun illumines this entire world, so the kṣetrin (knower) illumines the entire kṣetra. Śaṅkara reads kṛtsnaṁ lokaṁ as the standard Advaitic gloss on cidābhāsa: one consciousness lights up many fields.",
  '13.34': "Those who know with the eye of knowledge this distinction between kṣetra and kṣetrajña, and the liberation of beings from prakṛti, attain the supreme. Śaṅkara closes the chapter on jñāna-cakṣus — discrimination is the very organ of mokṣa.",
  '13.35': "(In the 35-verse vulgate this final summary verse repeats that those who, by the eye of knowledge, know the kṣetra-kṣetrajña distinction and the cessation of bhūta-prakṛti reach the supreme.) Śaṅkara takes it as the chapter's mahā-vākya-style colophon: jñāna alone, not karma, terminates saṁsāra.",

  // ── Chapter 14 — Guṇa-Traya Vibhāga Yoga ─────────────────────────────
  '14.1': "Kṛṣṇa announces that he will once more declare the supreme jñāna among knowledges — knowing which, all the munis went from this world to the highest perfection. Śaṅkara reads this as a deliberate re-emphasis: the same Self-knowledge of ch 13 is now being approached through the guṇa-analysis.",
  '14.2': "Those who, taking refuge in this knowledge, have reached his nature, are not born at the world's beginning nor disturbed at its dissolution. Śaṅkara: sādharmya here is identity-with-brahman, not similarity, since 'becoming Kṛṣṇa' must mean non-difference, not partnership.",
  '14.3': "His mahad-brahman is the womb in which he places the seed; from that arises the birth of all beings. Śaṅkara takes mahad-brahman as prakṛti acting as upādhi — Īśvara is the seed-giver and prakṛti the receptive matrix, a metaphor not a metaphysics.",
  '14.4': "Whatever forms come to be in any wombs, prakṛti is the great womb, and Kṛṣṇa is the seed-giving father. Śaṅkara: every species, every body, has the same single ground; difference is only in the prakṛti-modifications.",
  '14.5': "Sattva, rajas, and tamas, born of prakṛti, bind the imperishable embodied one in the body. Śaṅkara stresses dehinaṁ avyayaṁ — the Self is by nature unbindable; the binding is figurative, an upādhi-fastening, not a real chain.",
  '14.6': "Sattva, being pure, is illuminating and free from disease, but binds by attachment to happiness and to knowledge. Śaṅkara: even the highest guṇa binds, because clinging to sukha and jñāna keeps one on the seer-seen plane.",
  '14.7': "Rajas, characterised by passion, born of craving and attachment, binds the embodied one by attachment to action. Śaṅkara reads kāmika as the source of the entire pravṛtti-mārga — desire-driven action keeps saṁsāra in motion.",
  '14.8': "Tamas is born of ignorance, deluding all embodied beings, binding through inadvertence, indolence, and sleep. For Śaṅkara, ajñāna-jam tamas is the closest of the three to avidyā proper, the ground of all error.",
  '14.9': "Sattva binds to happiness, rajas to action, tamas to inadvertence by veiling knowledge. Śaṅkara: each guṇa has its signature shackle — pleasure, activity, dullness — and right diagnosis is half of liberation.",
  '14.10': "When one guṇa increases, it overcomes the other two — this is the constant interplay of the guṇas. Śaṅkara treats this as the empirical rule of inner weather: at any moment one guṇa is dominant; sādhana means engineering sattva to rise.",
  '14.11': "When at every gate of the body the light of knowledge shines, then sattva is preponderant. Śaṅkara: jñāna-prakāśa here is the indriya-mukha-clarity that sattva produces — discrimination feels effortless when sattva crests.",
  '14.12': "Greed, activity, undertaking of works, restlessness, longing — these arise when rajas dominates. Śaṅkara reads it as the catalogue of the kāmika-svabhāva, useful diagnostic signs.",
  '14.13': "Darkness, inertia, inadvertence, and delusion arise when tamas dominates. Śaṅkara: pramāda here is more than carelessness; it is the inability of the buddhi to even register the truth.",
  '14.14': "If the embodied dies when sattva is dominant, he goes to the spotless worlds of those who know the highest. Śaṅkara: sattva-mṛti yields a luminous gati but is still within saṁsāra — even svarga is a guṇa-fruit.",
  '14.15': "Dying in rajas, one is born among the action-attached; dying in tamas, one is born in deluded wombs. Śaṅkara reads this as the ethical lever: present guṇa-balance shapes the next janma.",
  '14.16': "The fruit of good action is sāttvika and pure; the fruit of rājasic action is pain; the fruit of tāmasic action is ignorance. Śaṅkara: the same triad classifies actions and their fruits — phala mirrors hetu.",
  '14.17': "From sattva arises knowledge, from rajas greed, from tamas inadvertence and delusion and ignorance. For Śaṅkara, this is the canonical effect-list of the guṇas, useful for recognising one's own state.",
  '14.18': "Sāttvikas go upward, rājasikas stay in the middle, tāmasikas — the ones grounded in the lowest guṇa — go downward. Śaṅkara takes the geography figuratively: ūrdhva and adhaḥ name better and worse births, not literal heights.",
  '14.19': "When the seer perceives no doer other than the guṇas, and knows what is beyond the guṇas, he attains his nature. Śaṅkara: this is the kūṭa-vākya of the chapter — kartā nānyaṁ guṇebhyaḥ is the categorical denial of the Self's doership.",
  '14.20': "Transcending the three guṇas which arise from the body, the embodied one, freed from the suffering of birth, death, and old age, attains immortality. Śaṅkara: amṛta here is mokṣa, defined precisely as the cessation of saṁsāra-duḥkha.",
  '14.21': "Arjuna asks: by what marks is the guṇa-transcender known, what is his conduct, how does he cross the guṇas? Śaṅkara structures the rest of the chapter as the answer to these three questions, parallel to the sthitaprajña-question of ch 2.",
  '14.22': "He who, when sattva, rajas, or tamas arises, neither hates nor longs for it when absent — Śaṅkara: indifference to the inner weather, not its abolition, is the first mark.",
  '14.23': "He who sits as if a witness, unmoved by the guṇas, knowing 'the guṇas are working' and stays put — Śaṅkara reads udāsīnavat as the precise stance of the sākṣin: present, aware, uninvolved.",
  '14.24': "Equal in pleasure and pain, self-poised, equal towards a clod, a stone, gold; equal towards the dear and the unloved, firm, equal in praise and blame — Śaṅkara: the samatva-list is not a stoic posture but the natural shape of one for whom upādhis no longer compel reaction.",
  '14.25': "Equal in honour and dishonour, equal towards friend and foe, abandoning all undertakings — he is called guṇa-transcender. Śaṅkara: sarvārambha-parityāgī confirms that the guṇātīta is also a saṁnyāsin in deed, not only in attitude.",
  '14.26': "He who serves Kṛṣṇa with unswerving bhakti-yoga, transcending the guṇas, becomes fit for becoming brahman. Śaṅkara: bhakti here is jñāna-niṣṭhā in another guise; brahma-bhūyāya kalpate confirms identity, not proximity.",
  '14.27': "I am the abode of brahman, of the immortal, the imperishable, of the eternal dharma, and of absolute bliss. Śaṅkara: brahmaṇaḥ pratiṣṭhā names Kṛṣṇa as nirupādhika brahman, the very svarūpa to which the chapter has been pointing.",

  // ── Chapter 15 — Puruṣottama Yoga ────────────────────────────────────
  '15.1': "The aśvattha tree, with roots above and branches below, whose leaves are the Vedas — he who knows it knows the Veda. Śaṅkara reads ūrdhva-mūla as brahman, the non-temporal source; adhaḥ-śākham as the saṁsāra-spread; the tree itself as the apparent saṁsāra-vṛkṣa, real-looking but cuttable by jñāna.",
  '15.2': "Its branches spread above and below, fed by the guṇas, with sense-objects as buds, and roots stretching downward in the world of men, binding by karma. Śaṅkara: each anatomical detail corresponds to a piece of saṁsāric machinery — the tree is an extended dṛṣṭānta of bondage.",
  '15.3': "Its form is not perceived here as it is — neither end, beginning, nor foundation. Śaṅkara: the tree's apparent realness is exactly avidyā's effect; its 'true form' as nothing is precisely what jñāna discloses.",
  '15.4': "Having cut this firmly-rooted aśvattha with the strong axe of non-attachment, one should seek the place from which there is no return. Śaṅkara takes asaṅga-śastreṇa as detachment in the form of viveka — vairāgya weaponised by jñāna.",
  '15.5': "Without pride and delusion, having conquered the evil of attachment, ever in adhyātma, with desires departed, freed from the dvandvas of pleasure and pain — the undeluded reach that imperishable place. Śaṅkara reads this as the standard sādhana-catuṣṭaya re-stated.",
  '15.6': "That place the sun does not illuminate, nor the moon, nor fire — having gone there, they do not return; that is my supreme abode. Śaṅkara: dhāma here is svarūpa-jyotis, self-luminous brahman; nivartante is the categorical end of rebirth.",
  '15.7': "An aṁśa of mine, becoming the eternal jīva in the world of beings, draws the senses with the mind as the sixth, all rooted in prakṛti. Śaṅkara: aṁśa is figurative; non-difference between jīva and Īśvara is the truth, but the upādhi-difference allows the part-language.",
  '15.8': "When the lord (jīva) takes a body, and when he leaves it, he carries these (mind and senses) with him as the wind carries fragrances from their seat. Śaṅkara: the līṅga-śarīra's transit explains continuity of saṁsāra across deaths without committing to any continuity of the Self.",
  '15.9': "Presiding over the ear, eye, touch, taste, smell, and the mind, he experiences sense-objects. Śaṅkara: 'experiences' here belongs to the upādhi-ridden jīva, not to the kūṭastha Self of ch 13.",
  '15.10': "The deluded do not see him as he leaves, stays, or experiences, yoked to the guṇas; those with the eye of knowledge see. Śaṅkara: jñāna-cakṣus is the recurrent organ — only it, not śruti or anumāna alone, finally discloses the witness.",
  '15.11': "The self-disciplined yogins, striving, see him seated in their own self; the unprepared, even striving, do not see him. Śaṅkara: akṛtātmānaḥ is the un-purified, the unfit; sādhana is precisely the polishing of the antaḥkaraṇa-mirror.",
  '15.12': "The light in the sun that illumines the whole world, in the moon, in fire — know that to be mine. Śaṅkara takes this as the unity-formula: every empirical light is the same caitanya, refracted through different upādhis.",
  '15.13': "Entering the earth I support beings by my power; becoming Soma full of sap I nourish the herbs. Śaṅkara: the cosmological roles are descriptions of Īśvara's saguṇa-aspect, didactically useful but ultimately to be sublated.",
  '15.14': "Becoming Vaiśvānara, lodged in the bodies of breathing beings, joined with prāṇa and apāna, I digest the four kinds of food. Śaṅkara: Vaiśvānara is here the digestive fire as a divine mode, not just a physiological function.",
  '15.15': "I am seated in the heart of all; from me come memory, knowledge, and their loss; I am all that is to be known by the Vedas, the maker of Vedānta, and the knower of the Veda. Śaṅkara: vedānta-kṛt and veda-vit are claimed by the Self for the Self — the Veda's whole point is precisely the Self.",
  '15.16': "There are two puruṣas in the world, the perishable and the imperishable; all beings are the perishable, the kūṭastha is the imperishable. Śaṅkara: kūṭastha is his technical word for the unchanging witness behind all change, distinct from the akṣara of ch 8.",
  '15.17': "But there is another, the supreme puruṣa, called paramātman — the imperishable Lord who, having entered the three worlds, supports them. Śaṅkara: this third term is brahman-as-Īśvara, transcending both kṣara and akṣara as the chapter's culminating term.",
  '15.18': "Because I transcend the perishable and am higher even than the imperishable, I am celebrated in the world and in the Veda as Puruṣottama. Śaṅkara: the title is etymological — 'highest among puruṣas' — and the rest of the chapter has earned it.",
  '15.19': "He who, undeluded, knows me thus as Puruṣottama, knows all and worships me with his whole being. For Śaṅkara, asaṁmūḍhaḥ is the technical mark of the brahmavid; sarvabhāva-bhajati is the niṣṭhā of total identity.",
  '15.20': "This most secret śāstra has thus been declared by me; knowing it, one becomes wise and his work is done. Śaṅkara closes the chapter by announcing kṛtakṛtya — the jñānin has nothing more to do, since jñāna is itself the goal.",

  // ── Chapter 16 — Daivāsura-Sampad Vibhāga Yoga ───────────────────────
  '16.1': "Fearlessness, purity of mind, steadfastness in jñāna-yoga, charity, self-control, sacrifice, study of scripture, austerity, and uprightness — Śaṅkara opens the daivī-sampat list as the catalogue of qualities that incline a person toward mokṣa.",
  '16.2': "Non-injury, truthfulness, absence of anger, renunciation, peacefulness, absence of calumny, compassion to beings, non-covetousness, gentleness, modesty, steadiness — Śaṅkara: each item supports either karma-yoga or directly jñāna-niṣṭhā.",
  '16.3': "Vigour, forgiveness, fortitude, purity, freedom from malice and from over-pride — these belong to one born for the divine wealth. Śaṅkara: nāti-mānitā stands out — even spiritual self-importance is on the asuric ledger.",
  '16.4': "Hypocrisy, arrogance, conceit, anger, harshness, ignorance — these are the marks of one born for the asuric wealth. Śaṅkara: this is the negative inventory; recognising these in oneself is the first step in transmutation.",
  '16.5': "The divine wealth leads to liberation, the asuric to bondage; do not grieve, Pārjuna, you are born to the divine. Śaṅkara: the typology is not racial or fated — it describes the predominant tendency at birth, alterable by effort.",
  '16.6': "Two kinds of beings exist in the world — daiva and āsura; daiva has been described, hear from me of the āsura. Śaṅkara: the chapter now turns to a sustained portrait of the asuric mind as a diagnostic device.",
  '16.7': "Asuric people know neither pravṛtti nor nivṛtti; in them is found neither purity, nor good conduct, nor truth. Śaṅkara: the absence of even basic dharma-discrimination is the structural mark of asuric ajñāna.",
  '16.8': "They say the world is unreal, without basis, without an Īśvara, born of mutual union — caused by lust alone. Śaṅkara reads this as a summary of cārvāka-style materialism, which he treats as the asuric philosophy par excellence.",
  '16.9': "Holding to this view, the lost-self ones of small intellect become enemies of the world, doing terrible deeds for its destruction. Śaṅkara: nāṣṭātmānaḥ is severe — they have lost contact with the very Self they deny in theory.",
  '16.10': "Resorting to insatiable kāma, full of hypocrisy, pride, and arrogance, they hold corrupt resolves through delusion and act with impure vows. Śaṅkara: dambha-māna-mada is the standard asuric triad echoing the previous list of vices.",
  '16.11': "Taking refuge in immeasurable cintā ending only at death, regarding kāma-bhoga as the highest, they are convinced 'this is everything'. Śaṅkara reads cintā as the asuric mind's defining tone — endless calculation in service of consumption.",
  '16.12': "Bound by hundreds of cords of expectation, given over to lust and anger, they strive to amass wealth by unjust means for the enjoyment of desires. Śaṅkara: āśāpāśa-śatair baddhāḥ — bondage is precisely āśā in his reading, not karma in the abstract.",
  '16.13': "'This I have gained today, this desire I shall fulfil; this wealth is mine and this also shall be mine' — Śaṅkara takes the inner monologue as itself the asuric reality, an actual citta-vṛtti pattern.",
  '16.14': "'That enemy I have slain; others I shall slay; I am the lord, the enjoyer, perfect, strong, happy' — Śaṅkara: īśvaro 'haṁ ahaṁ bhogī is the asuric pseudo-mahāvākya, a counterfeit aham.",
  '16.15': "'I am rich, well-born; who else is equal to me? I shall sacrifice, give, rejoice' — thus deluded by ignorance, they go on. Śaṅkara reads ajñāna-vimohitāḥ as the diagnostic — every asuric speech-act is rooted in primal avidyā.",
  '16.16': "Bewildered by many thoughts, enmeshed in a net of delusion, attached to the enjoyment of desires, they fall into a foul hell. Śaṅkara: aśucau narake here is the natural fruit, not an arbitrary punishment — it is what such conduct is.",
  '16.17': "Self-conceited, stubborn, full of pride and intoxication of wealth, they offer sacrifices nominally, with hypocrisy, not according to vidhi. Śaṅkara: even ritual, when asuric, becomes a vehicle of further ahaṅkāra rather than its dissolution.",
  '16.18': "Resorting to ahaṅkāra, force, pride, lust, and anger, they hate me in their own and others' bodies. Śaṅkara: dviṣantaḥ in svaparadeheṣu names the deepest asuric sin — hatred of the very Self that is one's own being.",
  '16.19': "Such cruel haters, the lowest of men, I cast forever into the wombs of asuras in the cycles of saṁsāra. Śaṅkara: Īśvara's 'casting' is figurative — it is their own karma-svabhāva that lands them there.",
  '16.20': "Reaching the asuric womb birth after birth, deluded, not attaining me, they go to the lowest gati. Śaṅkara: a-prāpya mām reminds the listener that the entire asuric arc is, structurally, the failure to recognise the Self as Kṛṣṇa.",
  '16.21': "Threefold is the gate of this naraka, destructive of the self — kāma, krodha, and lobha; therefore one should abandon these three. Śaṅkara: tri-vidhaṁ narakasya dvāram becomes the central ethical formula of the chapter — three vices, one hell.",
  '16.22': "Released from these three gates of darkness, a person practises what is good for the self, and so attains the supreme. Śaṅkara: śreyas-ācaraṇa is karma-yoga purifying the citta until jñāna can take hold.",
  '16.23': "He who, abandoning śāstra-injunctions, acts under the impulse of desire, attains neither perfection, nor happiness, nor the supreme goal. Śaṅkara: śāstra-vidhi is the safety-rail — without it kāma-cāra becomes the asuric default.",
  '16.24': "Therefore let śāstra be your authority for what is to be done and what is to be avoided; knowing the śāstra-injunction, you should act here. Śaṅkara closes the chapter by enthroning śāstra as pramāṇa for kāryākārya — a stance he treats as foundational for all later sādhana.",

  // ── Chapter 17 — Śraddhā-Traya Vibhāga Yoga ──────────────────────────
  '17.1': "Arjuna asks: those who, abandoning śāstra, sacrifice with śraddhā — what is their niṣṭhā: sāttvic, rājasic, or tāmasic? Śaṅkara: the question forces a typology of śraddhā itself, since śraddhā without śāstra is not automatically void.",
  '17.2': "The śraddhā of embodied beings is threefold, born of svabhāva — sāttvic, rājasic, and tāmasic; hear of it. Śaṅkara: svabhāva-jā here means resulting from saṁskāras of past births, not metaphysically fixed.",
  '17.3': "The śraddhā of each is in accord with his sattva (mind-stuff); the puruṣa is made of his śraddhā — as is his śraddhā, so is he. Śaṅkara: śraddhāmayo 'yaṁ puruṣaḥ is the central anthropological claim — a person is exactly what they trust.",
  '17.4': "Sāttvikas worship the gods, rājasikas the yakṣas and rākṣasas, tāmasikas the pretas and bhūta-gaṇas. Śaṅkara: the object of one's worship discloses the level of one's mind more reliably than the act of worship.",
  '17.5': "Those who, without śāstra-vidhāna, perform fierce tapas, full of hypocrisy and ahaṁkāra, joined with kāma, rāga, and force — Śaṅkara: a-śāstra-vihita-tapas is itself an asuric symptom, not just an error.",
  '17.6': "Tormenting the bhūta-grāma in their bodies and Me dwelling in the body — know them as asuric in resolve. Śaṅkara: ātma-pīḍā and bhagavat-pīḍā are linked — to mortify the body unjustly is to abuse the indwelling Self.",
  '17.7': "Food too is dear to each according to one's nature, and so are yajña, tapas, and dāna; hear their distinction. Śaṅkara structures the rest of the chapter as a fourfold guṇa-classification across these four domains.",
  '17.8': "Foods that promote longevity, sattva, strength, health, happiness, and friendliness — savoury, smooth, substantial, agreeable — are dear to sāttvikas. Śaṅkara: the criterion is effect on the antaḥkaraṇa, not mere caste-ritual purity.",
  '17.9': "Foods bitter, sour, salty, very hot, pungent, dry, and burning — dear to rājasikas, productive of pain, grief, and disease. Śaṅkara: rājasika-āhāra agitates rather than nourishes — the criterion remains effect on citta.",
  '17.10': "Stale, tasteless, foul-smelling, leftover, refuse, and impure — dear to tāmasikas. Śaṅkara: this is the most graphic of the three lists and intended to make the categories vivid.",
  '17.11': "Yajña offered according to vidhi, by those who do not desire the fruit, with the conviction 'this is to be done' — that is sāttvic. Śaṅkara: the absence of phala-saṅga is the central criterion of sāttvika-yajña, echoing the niṣkāma-karma of ch 3.",
  '17.12': "Yajña offered for the sake of fruit and for the sake of show — know that to be rājasic. Śaṅkara: phalābhisandhāna and dambha together corrupt the yajña even when the form is preserved.",
  '17.13': "Yajña without vidhi, without distribution of food, without mantras, dakṣiṇā, or śraddhā — they call tāmasic. Śaṅkara: each missing element is itself a marker — a yajña without śraddhā is not a yajña at all in his reading.",
  '17.14': "Worship of gods, brāhmaṇas, gurus, and the wise; purity, uprightness, brahmacarya, and non-injury — this is bodily tapas. Śaṅkara: śārīraṁ tapas is mostly conduct, not penance — habitual right behaviour treated as austerity.",
  '17.15': "Speech that does not agitate, truthful, agreeable, beneficial, and the practice of svādhyāya — that is verbal tapas. Śaṅkara: anudvegakaraṁ is the most demanding criterion — even true speech that wounds fails this test.",
  '17.16': "Cheerfulness of mind, gentleness, silence, self-control, purification of one's nature — that is mental tapas. Śaṅkara: the inner austerity is harder than the outer and is the indispensable foundation.",
  '17.17': "These three austerities, performed with supreme śraddhā by yoked men without longing for fruit, are called sāttvika. Śaṅkara: tri-vidhaṁ tapas done niṣkāma is essentially karma-yoga in austerity-form.",
  '17.18': "Tapas done for the sake of respect, honour, worship, with hypocrisy — that is rājasic, unstable and impermanent. Śaṅkara: even the form is the same; only the antaḥ-pravṛtti decides class.",
  '17.19': "Tapas done with deluded resolve, by self-torment, or with the aim of injuring another — that is tāmasic. Śaṅkara: parocchittaye is especially worth marking — abhicāra-tapas is the worst kind.",
  '17.20': "A gift given, with the conviction 'it is to be given', without expectation of return, in the right place, time, and to the right recipient — that is sāttvika. Śaṅkara: deśa-kāla-pātra triad becomes the formula for sāttvika-dāna.",
  '17.21': "A gift given expecting return, or aiming at fruit, or unwillingly — that is rājasic. Śaṅkara: even slight reluctance taints the gift; sāttvic giving is open-handed without inner accounting.",
  '17.22': "A gift given at the wrong place, wrong time, to an unfit recipient, without honour or with contempt — that is tāmasic. Śaṅkara: dāna mis-targeted is not merely wasted but karmically negative.",
  '17.23': "OM TAT SAT — this triad is the threefold designation of brahman, by which the brāhmaṇas, the Vedas, and the yajñas were ordained of old. Śaṅkara: the trika is not three names but three aspects of one indication of brahman.",
  '17.24': "Therefore acts of yajña, dāna, and tapas, done by those who utter brahman, always begin with OM as ordained by śāstra. Śaṅkara: praṇava-uccāraṇa is the symbolic anchoring of every act in brahman.",
  '17.25': "Aiming at no fruit, the seekers of mokṣa do their various acts of yajña, tapas, and dāna with the utterance 'TAT'. Śaṅkara: TAT signals dedication-to-brahman and abandonment of phala — the niṣkāma-stamp.",
  '17.26': "SAT is used in the sense of being and goodness; in praiseworthy action, the word SAT is also applied. Śaṅkara: the etymology supports both metaphysical and ethical readings, and these merge in the sat-act.",
  '17.27': "Steadfastness in yajña, tapas, and dāna is also called SAT, and an action for the sake of these is also called SAT. Śaṅkara: the application of SAT to means as well as to brahman shows the continuity between sādhana and goal.",
  '17.28': "Whatever oblation, gift, tapas, or any act done without śraddhā is called asat — it is nothing here and nothing hereafter. Śaṅkara: a-śraddhayā kṛtam is the chapter's last word — without trust the entire structure collapses, no matter the form.",

  // ── Chapter 18 — Mokṣa-Saṁnyāsa Yoga ─────────────────────────────────
  '18.1': "Arjuna asks for the distinct truth of saṁnyāsa and tyāga. Śaṅkara: the chapter's opening question forces the precise distinction his entire bhāṣya pivots on — saṁnyāsa as renunciation of all action, tyāga as renunciation of fruit alone.",
  '18.2': "The wise call the giving up of kāmya-karmas saṁnyāsa; the abandonment of the fruit of all karmas the discerning call tyāga. Śaṅkara accepts this provisional distinction but holds that paramārthika saṁnyāsa is the renunciation of doership itself, available only to the jñānin.",
  '18.3': "Some thinkers say all action should be abandoned as flawed; others say acts of yajña, dāna, and tapas should never be given up. Śaṅkara: the second school is correct for the karma-yogin; the first becomes correct only after jñāna dawns.",
  '18.4': "Hear my conclusion regarding tyāga — tyāga has been declared to be of three kinds. Śaṅkara: niścaya is the operative word — the Lord's verdict, not yet another opinion.",
  '18.5': "Acts of yajña, dāna, and tapas are not to be given up, but performed; for they purify the discerning. Śaṅkara: pāvanāni manīṣiṇām — these acts are not for the jñānin himself but for the citta-śuddhi of the seeker.",
  '18.6': "Even these acts should be done having abandoned attachment and fruit — this is my well-considered, supreme view. Śaṅkara: phala-tyāga in the very performance is the central mantra of niṣkāma-karma-yoga.",
  '18.7': "Abandonment of niyata (prescribed) karma is not appropriate; its abandonment from delusion is called tāmasic. Śaṅkara: even renunciation can be tāmasic if done through inertia or confusion rather than discrimination.",
  '18.8': "Abandoning karma as 'painful', from fear of bodily trouble — that is rājasic tyāga, and one does not gain its fruit. Śaṅkara: aversion-driven renunciation does not earn any tyāga-phala, only re-enmeshment.",
  '18.9': "When niyata-karma is done thinking 'it is to be done', having abandoned attachment and fruit — that is sāttvika tyāga in my view. Śaṅkara: kartavyam eveti is the niṣṭhā-marker — duty for its own sake, framed by jñāna.",
  '18.10': "The wise tyāgī of pure sattva, neither hates the disagreeable act nor is attached to the agreeable, severed from doubts. Śaṅkara: chinna-saṁśayaḥ already foreshadows the brahmavid — sāttvika-tyāga is already on the slope to jñāna.",
  '18.11': "It is not possible for an embodied to abandon karmas entirely; one who abandons the fruit of karma is called the tyāgī. Śaṅkara: phala-tyāgin is the maximum saṁnyāsa available short of full jñāna-niṣṭhā.",
  '18.12': "For non-tyāgins the threefold fruit — desired, undesired, mixed — accrues after death, but never for saṁnyāsins. Śaṅkara: saṁnyāsi here means the brahmavid for whom karma has no further phala, since doership has dissolved.",
  '18.13': "Hear from me the five causes of all action declared in the sāṁkhya-conclusion. Śaṅkara: the kāraṇa-pañcaka is the central analytic of the chapter, designed to dislodge ahaṅkāric doership.",
  '18.14': "The seat (body), the doer (jīva), the various instruments, the various separate efforts, and the divine — these five. Śaṅkara: daiva is the fifth cause and prevents the list from collapsing into pure puruṣa-kāra.",
  '18.15': "Whatever karma a person undertakes by body, speech, or mind, whether right or contrary, these five are its causes. Śaṅkara: even thought-actions have all five — there is no purely autonomous mental act.",
  '18.16': "Therefore he who, of un-cultured mind, sees the kevala-ātman as the doer — that fool does not see. Śaṅkara: this is the chapter's central jñāna-thesis — to see the Self as kartā is the root error.",
  '18.17': "He whose state is free of ahaṁkāra, whose buddhi is untainted — even slaying these worlds, he neither slays nor is bound. Śaṅkara takes this as the categorical jīvanmukti claim — non-doership is real, not metaphorical, when ahaṅkāra is gone.",
  '18.18': "Knowledge, the known, the knower — the threefold karma-codanā; instrument, action, agent — the threefold karma-saṁgraha. Śaṅkara: the chapter now classifies each component of action by the three guṇas in turn.",
  '18.19': "Knowledge, action, and agent are declared as threefold, by guṇa-difference, in the sāṁkhya enumeration; hear them too. Śaṅkara: the upcoming triads are sāṁkhyokta in the sense of well-classified, not Sāṁkhya-school doctrine.",
  '18.20': "Knowledge by which one sees the one imperishable being in all beings, undivided in the divided — that is sāttvika jñāna. Śaṅkara: this verse is, for him, the Gītā's most concise definition of brahmajñāna.",
  '18.21': "Knowledge that, in all beings, sees various entities as separate, manifold — that is rājasika. Śaṅkara: pṛthaktva-jñāna is samsāric vyavahāra-buddhi at its most refined, still bondage.",
  '18.22': "That which clings to one effect as if it were the whole, without reasoning or truth, narrow — is tāmasika. Śaṅkara: ekasmin kārye saktam names every kind of fanaticism that locks onto a single object.",
  '18.23': "Niyata karma, done without attachment, without rāga or dveṣa, by one who does not desire the fruit — that is sāttvika. Śaṅkara: this is karma-yoga's portrait one more time, now under the guṇa-trika.",
  '18.24': "Karma done with much exertion by one desiring objects of desire, or out of ahaṁkāra — that is rājasika. Śaṅkara: bahulāyāsam itself is the marker — sāttvic action feels effortless even when costly.",
  '18.25': "Karma undertaken in delusion, without regard to consequence, loss, injury, or one's capacity — that is tāmasika. Śaṅkara: anavekṣya is fourfold negligence, each a sufficient marker.",
  '18.26': "Free from attachment, non-egoistic, full of dhṛti and utsāha, unmoved in success and failure — such an agent is sāttvika. Śaṅkara: the kartṛ-trika echoes the sthitaprajña-mark of ch 2 and the bhakta-mark of ch 12.",
  '18.27': "Attached, fruit-seeking, greedy, injurious, impure, full of harṣa-śoka — that agent is rājasika. Śaṅkara: harṣa-śokānvitaḥ is decisive — the inner oscillation marks the rāja-kartṛ.",
  '18.28': "Unyoked, vulgar, stubborn, deceitful, cruel, lazy, given to despair, procrastinating — that agent is tāmasika. Śaṅkara: dīrgha-sūtrī, the procrastinator, is given as a defining tāmasika trait.",
  '18.29': "Hear now of the threefold division of buddhi and dhṛti by guṇa, fully and separately. Śaṅkara: the triad is now applied to the inner instruments themselves, the most diagnostic of all.",
  '18.30': "The buddhi that knows pravṛtti and nivṛtti, what to do and what not, fear and fearlessness, bondage and liberation — that is sāttvika. Śaṅkara: a sāttvika intellect is precisely viveka-buddhi, the foundation of all sādhana.",
  '18.31': "The buddhi that wrongly grasps dharma and adharma, what is to be done and what is not — that is rājasika. Śaṅkara: this is the cleverness that mis-categorises kāryākārya, often confidently.",
  '18.32': "The buddhi that, enveloped in tamas, takes adharma as dharma and reverses every meaning — that is tāmasika. Śaṅkara: viparīta-buddhi is the most dangerous, since the very organ of decision has been inverted.",
  '18.33': "The dhṛti by which one holds together the activities of mind, prāṇa, and senses, with unwavering yoga — that is sāttvika. Śaṅkara: dhṛti is the inner steadiness without which jñāna cannot mature.",
  '18.34': "The dhṛti by which one holds dharma, kāma, and artha with attachment, longing for fruit — that is rājasika. Śaṅkara: even dhṛti can be guṇa-coloured; sāttvic dhṛti targets only what supports mokṣa.",
  '18.35': "The dhṛti by which the dull-witted does not abandon sleep, fear, grief, despair, and intoxication — that is tāmasika. Śaṅkara: this is the negative tenacity that holds onto exactly what should be released.",
  '18.36': "Hear now from me of the threefold sukha — that in which one delights from practice and reaches the end of pain. Śaṅkara: sukha is also guṇa-coded, and the sāttvika is the only one that delivers duḥkha-anta.",
  '18.37': "What at first seems like poison and afterwards like nectar — born of buddhi-prasāda — that sukha is sāttvika. Śaṅkara: ātma-buddhi-prasāda-jam locates the sāttvika sukha in the very clearing of the antaḥkaraṇa.",
  '18.38': "What from indriya-artha-saṁyoga is at first like nectar and afterwards like poison — that sukha is rājasika. Śaṅkara: bhoga-sukha is structurally inverted; its inevitable pariṇāma is duḥkha.",
  '18.39': "What deludes from beginning to end, born of sleep, indolence, and inadvertence — that sukha is tāmasika. Śaṅkara: tāmasic 'happiness' is sleep mistaken for peace.",
  '18.40': "There is no being on earth or among the gods in heaven free from these three guṇas of prakṛti. Śaṅkara: the universal scope is given so that no one can claim guṇa-exemption — sādhana has to negotiate this terrain.",
  '18.41': "The duties of brāhmaṇas, kṣatriyas, vaiśyas, and śūdras are distributed by the guṇas born of their svabhāva. Śaṅkara: svabhāva-prabhava is past saṁskāra-ripening; the varṇa-system is here described, not metaphysically eternalised.",
  '18.42': "Calmness, self-control, tapas, purity, forbearance, uprightness, knowledge, vijñāna, and faith — the brāhmaṇa-karma born of svabhāva. Śaṅkara: the list is functional, not hereditary — these are the inner marks.",
  '18.43': "Heroism, vigour, dhṛti, dexterity, not retreating in battle, charity, lordliness — the kṣatriya-karma born of svabhāva. Śaṅkara: each duty-set is a sādhana through which one's own guṇa-mix can be brought to sattva.",
  '18.44': "Agriculture, cattle-tending, and trade — the vaiśya-karma; service-natured action — the śūdra-karma. Śaṅkara: paricaryātmakam is a description of role, not of value; mokṣa-fitness is independent of varṇa.",
  '18.45': "Each man, devoted to his own sva-karma, attains perfection; hear how, devoted to his own karma, he reaches it. Śaṅkara: sva-karma-niratah is the karma-yoga formula scaled to one's particular varṇa-station.",
  '18.46': "He from whom is the activity of beings, by whom all this is pervaded — worshipping him by one's own karma, a person attains perfection. Śaṅkara: sva-karma is itself transmutable into worship of Īśvara through bhāva.",
  '18.47': "Better one's own dharma, even imperfectly performed, than another's well done; doing svabhāva-niyata karma, one incurs no fault. Śaṅkara: svabhāva-niyatam reinforces that sva-dharma is not arbitrary but rooted in one's actual constitution.",
  '18.48': "Sahaja karma should not be abandoned, though attended with defect; for all undertakings are enveloped in defect, as fire by smoke. Śaṅkara: doṣa here is the inevitable hiṁsā or trouble of any worldly act — that is no reason to flee karma if one is not yet jñāna-ripe.",
  '18.49': "He whose buddhi is unattached everywhere, who has won self, whose desires have departed — by saṁnyāsa attains the supreme niṣkarmya-siddhi. Śaṅkara: naiṣkarmya-siddhi is his technical name for the state where action ceases to bind because doership is gone.",
  '18.50': "Hear from me how, having attained siddhi, one attains brahman, that supreme niṣṭhā of jñāna. Śaṅkara: jñāna-niṣṭhā is the chapter's culminating term — the abiding-in of the realised, not a fresh acquisition.",
  '18.51': "With pure buddhi, controlling the self by dhṛti, abandoning sound and the other objects, casting off attraction and aversion — Śaṅkara: this verse begins the most concentrated jñāna-niṣṭhā prescription in the Gītā for him.",
  '18.52': "Resorting to a solitary place, eating little, with body, speech, and mind controlled, ever joined with dhyāna-yoga, taking refuge in vairāgya — Śaṅkara: vairāgya here is not just attitude but the enabling environment of the niṣṭhā.",
  '18.53': "Forsaking ahaṁkāra, force, pride, kāma, krodha, and parigraha, free from possessiveness, peaceful — he is fit for becoming brahman. Śaṅkara: brahma-bhūyāya kalpate names not a future event but the structural fitness for non-difference.",
  '18.54': "Having become brahman, of serene self, he neither grieves nor longs; equal to all beings, he gains supreme bhakti to me. Śaṅkara: parām bhakti here is the post-jñāna nature of the realised — not a means but the form of liberation.",
  '18.55': "By bhakti he knows me — what extent and who I really am; then, having known me in truth, he enters me. Śaṅkara: tato māṁ tattvato jñātvā places jñāna decisively after bhakti as its fruit, then identifies entry-into-Kṛṣṇa with mokṣa.",
  '18.56': "Even doing all karmas always, taking refuge in me, by my grace he attains the eternal imperishable place. Śaṅkara: Īśvara-prasāda is the device by which karma-yoga's continuing action does not bind the realised.",
  '18.57': "Mentally renouncing all karmas in me, fixed on me as the goal, resorting to buddhi-yoga — be thou ever mind-fixed on me. Śaṅkara: cetasā saṁnyasya names the renunciation that is internal, possible even in apparent action.",
  '18.58': "Mind-fixed on me, you will cross all difficulties by my grace; but if from ahaṁkāra you do not heed, you will perish. Śaṅkara: ahaṁkāra is the one obstacle that cancels the entire teaching, hence the personal warning to Arjuna.",
  '18.59': "If, taking refuge in ahaṁkāra, you think 'I shall not fight', that resolve is vain — your prakṛti will compel you. Śaṅkara: prakṛtis tvāṁ niyokṣyati is decisive — refusal of one's svabhāva-karma is not freedom but illusion.",
  '18.60': "Bound by your sva-karma born of svabhāva, what you do not wish to do from delusion, you will do helplessly. Śaṅkara: this is the karmic determinism for the unliberated — only jñāna breaks the circuit.",
  '18.61': "Īśvara dwells in the heart of all beings, causing them to revolve as on a yantra by his māyā. Śaṅkara: hṛd-deśe sarva-bhūtānām makes the inner-controller doctrine personal; māyā is his standard term for the apparent yantra-mechanism.",
  '18.62': "Take refuge in him alone with all your being; by his grace you will attain supreme peace, the eternal abode. Śaṅkara: śaraṇaṁ gaccha sarva-bhāvena is the chapter's bhakti-summary, but the abode reached is the same brahman.",
  '18.63': "Thus the most secret jñāna has been declared to you by me; reflecting upon it fully, do as you wish. Śaṅkara: yathecchasi tathā kuru is teacher-restraint — the disciple's freedom is preserved, but the responsibility is now his.",
  '18.64': "Hear once more my supreme word, the most secret of all; you are dearly loved by me, therefore I will speak what is good for you. Śaṅkara: the repeated 'most secret' marks each escalation of the upadeśa.",
  '18.65': "Be mind-fixed on me, my devotee, sacrificing to me, bowing to me; you will come to me — truth, I promise; you are dear to me. Śaṅkara: the single-pointed manmanā formula compresses the entire bhakti-yoga and is, for him, ultimately jñāna-niṣṭhā.",
  '18.66': "Abandoning all dharmas, take refuge in me alone; I shall liberate you from all sins — do not grieve. Śaṅkara: sarva-dharmān parityajya is the categorical saṁnyāsa-vidhi — every prescribed act is to be given up by the realised; the rest must wait.",
  '18.67': "This is never to be told to one without tapas, without bhakti, who does not desire to hear, who scoffs at me. Śaṅkara: the adhikāra-rule is strict — the teaching is for the prepared seeker, not for the public.",
  '18.68': "He who teaches this most secret śāstra to my bhaktas, doing supreme bhakti to me, will come to me without doubt. Śaṅkara: parām bhaktiṁ kṛtvā links the teaching of the doctrine to the teacher's own niṣṭhā.",
  '18.69': "No one among men is dearer to me than he, nor will another on earth be dearer. Śaṅkara: the praise of the teacher is not flattery but acknowledgment that propagation of jñāna is the highest service.",
  '18.70': "He who studies this dharmya-saṁvāda of ours — by him I shall be worshipped through jñāna-yajña; this is my view. Śaṅkara: adhyayana of the Gītā is itself jñāna-yajña, a sacrificial act of cognition.",
  '18.71': "Even the man who, with śraddhā and free from hostility, only listens, is liberated and reaches the happy worlds of the meritorious. Śaṅkara: śravaṇa alone earns puṇyaloka; full mokṣa requires the further niṣṭhā but śravaṇa is no small thing.",
  '18.72': "Has this been heard by you with one-pointed mind, Pārtha? Has your delusion of ignorance been destroyed? Śaṅkara: the question is the teacher's standard pramāṇa-check — the disciple must report.",
  '18.73': "Arjuna replies: my delusion is destroyed, smṛti is regained by your grace; I stand firm, doubts gone, and shall do your word. Śaṅkara: smṛti-lābha is the recovery of svarūpa-smaraṇa, and karoṣye vacanaṁ tava is the proper post-jñāna stance.",
  '18.74': "Sañjaya: thus I have heard this wonderful dialogue between Vāsudeva and the great-souled Pārtha, causing my hair to stand on end. Śaṅkara: the dialogue's frame returns to remind the audience that the entire Gītā has been overheard, not directly experienced.",
  '18.75': "By the grace of Vyāsa I heard this supreme yoga of secrets directly from Kṛṣṇa, the master of yoga, declared by him in person. Śaṅkara: Vyāsa-prasāda highlights the lineage that delivers the teaching — even Sañjaya's hearing is mediated.",
  '18.76': "O king, recalling this wonderful and holy dialogue between Keśava and Arjuna, I rejoice again and again. Śaṅkara: smaraṇa of the dialogue is itself a sādhana — meritorious recall of the upadeśa.",
  '18.77': "Recalling that most wonderful form of Hari, my wonder is great, O king, and I rejoice again and again. Śaṅkara: the rūpa-smaraṇa here refers back to the viśva-rūpa of ch 11, the chapter's bhakti-anchor.",
  '18.78': "Where there is Kṛṣṇa, master of yoga, and Pārtha, the archer, there are fortune, victory, prosperity, and steady niti — this is my view. Śaṅkara: the closing śloka makes Kṛṣṇa-Arjuna togetherness the formula for śreyas — for him, the inner meaning is that wherever jñāna and adhikāra are joined, mokṣa is assured."
};
